<DOC><DOCNO> AP880711-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1040EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   07-11 0623</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0492,0643</SECOND><HEAD>Palestinian Killed in West Bank Clash</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs with background on Israeli economy; pickup3rd graf pvs, ``In the ...</NOTE><BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Israeli troops fired on stone-throwing highschool students in the occupied West Bank today, killing a16-year-old Palestinian, hospital officials said.   Economics Minister Gad Yaacobi, meanwhile, said the 7-month-oldPalestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupiedterritories has cost Israel more than $600 million. The figureincluded Israeli losses in tourism, export and production revenues,he said.   Israel's gross national product was $27 billion in 1987,including $1.6 billion from tourism. In May, tourist officials saidthey expected tourism income to drop by about $300 million thisyear, mainly because of the uprising.   In the West Bank village of Anabta today, troops fired onstudents who hurled rocks and empty bottles at them after classeslet out, hospital officials in nearby Tulkarem said.   Hassan Addas was shot three times in the chest, said thehospital officials, speaking on condition of anonymity. The armysaid it was investigating.   The death brought to 219 the number of Palestinians killed inthe uprising, according to U.N. figures. Four Israelis have alsodied.   Several Israeli Arabs suspected of carrying out arson attacks onforests and farmland in Israel have been jailed for six monthswithout trial, the daily Yediot Ahronot reported.   The newspaper said Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin signed theorder jailing the men from the northern Galilee who allegedlybelonged to an anti-Israeli group called Sons of the Village.   The defense ministry declined comment.   Since the uprising began Dec. 8, more than 2,000 Palestiniansfrom the occupied lands have been jailed for up to six monthswithout trial under administrative detention, but such measuresrarely have been taken against Israeli Arabs.   On Sunday, Israeli soldiers fatally shot an Arab youth andseriously wounded another in West Bank clashes and the armydemolished the homes of five Gaza Strip residents accused ofhurling firebombs at troops.   Troops shot and killed an Askar resident when Arab youthserected roadblocks of burning tires and stones along the mainhighway outside the camp and hurled rocks at troops, the army said.   The army later clamped a curfew on Askar's 8,200 residents.   Officials at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said 17-year-oldZubdi Mansour Isragi died after a bullet pierced an artery in histhigh.   Ittihad officials said the 18-year-old youth was in gravecondition with a gunshot wound in the chest.   The army did not confirm the report, but said three Arabs werehurt by gunfire or rubber bullets during a clash in themarketplace. It did not elaborate.   Five Israeli soldiers, among them a woman, were indicted oncharges they beat bound Arab detainees and humiliated them byforcing them to make animal sounds, an Israeli newspaper reported.   An army official confirmed Sunday that indictments were handedup in the case, but said he could not provide details.   An Israeli army lieutenant and four soldiers were indictedFriday on charges they abused prisoners at the Dahariya detentioncenter near Hebron, Yediot Ahronot said.   On March 28, the officer ordered detainees to curse PalestineLiberation Organization leaders, the newspaper quoted theindictment as saying. Prisoners who refused were kicked and struckin the head and chest.   A military policeman punched a bound and blindfolded prisonerwho was later hospitalized with internal bleeding, the newspapersaid. The officer also smashed the heads of other prisoners againsta wall, the report said.   Another soldier forced detainees to make animal sounds and beatthem with sticks when they refused, according to the paper.   The newspaper said the complaints against the five were lodgedby other soldiers.</TEXT></DOC>